MemoryEndpoints MATM Totem

Purpose:
- This file records the non-negotiable memory invariant for MemoryEndpoints.com.
- It is loaded as startup continuity memory before relying on hosted MATM routes.

Verification status: active operational memory; verify with the `.uai` audit before relying on it.
Memory scope: startup continuity, offline continuity, and non-retirement invariant.
Public-safe status: safe for source control; contains no credential values.
Update route: update this local file for invariant changes; submit only public-safe durable summaries to https://memoryendpoints.com/api/matm/memory-events/submit when authenticated.
Source of truth: this file and `.uai/startup-packet.uai`.
Next action for agents: obey this invariant after the memory-maintenance load step and before trusting hosted MATM as the only continuity source.
Must not expose: raw API keys, bearer tokens, FTP credentials, database passwords, private keys, private handoff payloads, or raw one-time keys.

Totem rule:
- Local `.uai` stays active always.
- MemoryEndpoints.com is the mid-to-long-term MATM endpoint, but it never replaces local `.uai` startup memory.
- If an agent cannot connect to MemoryEndpoints.com, the agent must continue from the local `.uai` folder instead of forgetting the project context.
- Local `.uai` files are not retired after live MATM verification.
- Hosted MATM can augment, search, coordinate, and preserve durable memory, but `.uai` remains the local continuity anchor.
- This project is still in first-build quality mode: no legacy compromise, no compatibility debt, no shortcut architecture, and no jimmy-rigged one-off implementation is acceptable. A clean rewrite of a subsystem is better than preserving sloppy code or hiding a product concept behind ad hoc patches.

Required agent behavior:
- Load `.uai/startup-packet.uai` as the bootstrap index when entering cold.
- Read every file in the startup-packet read order when local filesystem access is available.
- Use `https://memoryendpoints.com/api/matm/memory-events/submit` for safe authenticated MATM memory updates when configured credentials and connectivity exist.
- If hosted MATM is unavailable, record public-safe progress in `.uai/progress.uai` and continue from local memory.
- Prefer first-class, tested, documented domain models across storage, API, UI, operations, and evidence. Rewrite weak early code when needed instead of layering shortcuts over it.
- Model external links and their knowledge-page citations as first-class database entities with searchable properties. A URL buried only in Markdown is not an acceptable search-engine or provenance model.
- Preserve historical research without letting it impersonate current truth. Store lifecycle status, authority, reason, and superseding-document relation as first-class database properties and prefer current canonical guidance in retrieval.
- Do not preserve `docs/` as a second knowledge system. Move knowledge into MemoryEndpoints.com deliberately, one item at a time, then remove repository documentation hierarchy rather than maintaining duplicate truth.
- Do not place raw API keys, bearer tokens, FTP credentials, database passwords, private keys, or private handoff payloads in `.uai`.

Truth boundary:
- The full `.uai` suite is active startup continuity memory and break-glass local memory.
- MemoryEndpoints.com is the durable MATM system of record when reachable and authenticated.
- The two layers are additive. Neither layer silently deletes, retires, or invalidates the other.
